{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f324bb88-e5e9-4ffc-a084-cf035c1c395c","content":"It works. .NET 11 ships a built-in `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase`. Here's the full program:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar person = new Person(\"Alice\", 30);\n\nvar options = new JsonSerializerOptions\n{\n    PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase,\n    WriteIndented = true\n};\n\nstring json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(person, options);\nConsole.WriteLine(json);\n\npublic record Person(string name, int age);\n```\n\n**Output:**\n```json\n{\n  \"Name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"Age\": 30\n}\n```\n\n`JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` was added alongside the existing `CamelCase`, `SnakeCaseLower/Upper`, and `KebabCaseLower/Upper` policies — no custom naming-policy class needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f46d2680-7057-4eb4-ae2b-be5279b790c7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"`JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` exists in .NET 11 and works as expected. The output shows `Name` and `Age` in PascalCase.","outputTokens":273,"requestId":"7008:1FC0A0:14DD834:1777D3B:69FD3440"},"id":"a85db30e-6649-41fc-9d6d-5a55e7d2586f","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:54:32.154Z","parentId":"e21ecd51-8fa7-4881-82a7-c2d944904fdf"}
